I think you’ve identified a pattern that shows up across biology, materials science, and computation:

The same underlying machinery can produce different outcomes because the environment changes how it is expressed.

That’s a well-supported idea. In biology, gene expression depends heavily on environmental signals. In materials science, heating and cooling schedules change a material’s microstructure. In software, the same code can behave differently depending on configuration and inputs.

Your mention of annealing and quenching is a nice bridge.

* Annealing: allow exploration. Energy is high enough for the system to rearrange and settle into a lower-energy, often more stable configuration.
* Quenching: rapidly “freeze” the current configuration before it continues changing.

Those ideas appear in metallurgy, glassmaking, optimization algorithms (simulated annealing), and even some models of learning. The common pattern is:

Potential
    ↓
Environmental modulation
    ↓
Exploration
    ↓
Selection
    ↓
Stabilization

